'''Cobham plc''' ({{lse|COB}}) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] manufacturing company based in [[Wimborne Minster]], [[Dorset]], [[England]]. It is listed on the [[London Stock Exchange]] and is a constituent of the [[FTSE 250 Index]]. As of early 2011, Cobham ranks 33rd on ''[[Flight International]]'s'' list of the Top 100 Top aerospace firms, 35th on the ''[[Defense News]]'' list of Top 100 defense contractors, and 98th on ''[[Washington Technology]]'s'' list of Top 100 US government contractors.<ref>[http://washingtontechnology.com/toplists/top-100-lists/2010.aspx Washington Technology]</ref>

==History==
* 1934: Cobham was founded as '''Flight Refuelling Limited''' (FRL) by Sir [[Alan Cobham]]<ref name=history>[http://www.cobham.com/about-cobham/heritage.aspx Cobham: Our heritage]</ref> at [[RAF Ford]] in [[Sussex]].
* Shortly after the outbreak of [[World War II]]: FRL moved to [[RAF Tarrant Rushton|Tarrant Rushton]] in [[Dorset]].
* 1948: FRL was the first contractor to join the [[Berlin airlift]].<ref name=history/>
* 1949: FRL developed the 'probe and drogue' method of [[Aerial refueling|air-to-air refuelling]].<ref name=history/>
* 1970s: FRL transferred its aerial operations to [[Bournemouth Airport|Hurn Airport]].<ref>[http://www.south-coast-central.co.uk/avon_valley/avon-valley.htm Valley of the Avon]</ref>
* 1996: [[ML Aviation]] took over [[Nash & Thompson]], a major competitor.<ref>[http://home.comcast.net/~aero51/html/history/mlaviation.htm ML Aviation]</ref>
* September 1997: Cobham bought ML Aviation.<ref>[http://www.ukbusinesspark.co.uk/cobhamaa.htm UK Business Park]</ref>
* 2008: Cobham purchases [[S-TEC Corporation]], maker of general aviation autopilots for $38 million.<ref>{{cite journal|magazine=Flying Magazine|date=Feb 2008|pp=24}}</ref>
* February 2008: Cobham bought the [[sensor]] and [[Antenna (radio)|antenna]] systems division of [[BAE Systems]] for $240 million.<ref>[http://www.theengineer.co.uk/Articles/304759/Cobham+buys+BAE+Systems+division.htm Cobham buys BAE Systems Division] The Engineer, 25 February 2008</ref>
* June 2008 Cobham acquired [[Sparta Inc.]], a [[United States|US]] defence business, for $416 million.<ref>[http://www.rfglobalnet.com/article.mvc/Cobham-To-Purchase-SPARTA-For-416-Million-0001?VNETCOOKIE=NO Cobham to purchase Sparta for $416m] RF Globalnet, 16 January 2008</ref> It was renamed [[Cobham Analytic Solutions]].
* September 2008: Cobham completed the purchase of the [[radio frequency]] components business of [[M/A-COM]] for $425 million.<ref>[http://tycoelectronics.mediaroom.com/index.php?s=43&item=280 Tyco Electronics Announces Agreement to Sell Its RF Components and Subsystem Business To Cobham Plc] Tyco Press Release, 13 May 2008</ref>
* Early 2009, [[National Jet Systems]] renamed itself as Cobham (known as Cobham Aviation Services Australia or CAvSA) in line with a global Cobham rebranding initiative by its parent company Cobham plc.
* April 2009: Cobham agreed to purchase ''Argotek Inc.'', a provider of high-end [[information assurance]] services to the [[United States Intelligence Community]], for $36 million.<ref>[http://www.cobham.com/media/50264/278%20cobham%20acquires%20us%20national%20security%20company%20for%20us$36m%20final.pdf Cobham Reaches Agreement To Acquire US National Security Company For US$36.25 Million] Cobham Press Release, 6 Apr 2009</ref>
* June 2009: A Cobham - [[Northrop Grumman]] 50-50 joint venture won the U.S. Army's US$2.4 billion competition to supply Vehicular Intercom Systems.<ref>[http://www.cobham.com/media/68477/288%20u.s.%20army%20selects%20northrop%20grumman,%20cobham%20team%20to%20provide%20vis-x%20vehicular%20intercom%20systems.pdf U.S. Army Selects Northrop Grumman, Cobham Team To Provide VIS-X Vehicular Intercom Systems] Cobham News Release, 29 June 2009</ref>
* October 2011: Cobham Analytic Solutions sold for $350 million to the privately owned Parsons Corporation.<ref>[http://www.cobhaminvestors.com/news-item&item=808263452998726 COBHAM AGREES DIVESTMENT OF ANALYTIC SOLUTIONS BUSINESS FOR US$350M]</ref>

==Operations==
Cobham is organised into four core technology divisions: Mission Systems, Defence Systems, Avionics and Surveillance, and Aviation Services.

The Cobham Mission Systems Division claims to be the world market leader in [[aerial refuelling]]<ref>[http://www.cobham.com/about-cobham/mission-systems.aspx About Cobham - Mission Systems]</ref>, and provides a comprehensive range of weapons carriage and release equipment. Cobham Mission Systems also specialises in life support and personal survival equipment for aviators and astronauts.

The Cobham Defence Systems Division specialises in [[radar]], communication and [[electronic warfare]] systems, and claims to be the world leader in advanced tactical military vehicle [[intercom]] systems.<ref>[http://www.cobham.com/media/79447/304%20cobham%20awarded%20us%20$40m%20contract%20for%20digital%20vehicle%20intercom%20systems.pdf Cobham Awarded US$40m Contract for Digital Vehicle Intercom Systems]</ref>

The Cobham Avionics and Surveillance Division provides a range of electronic products for airborne, marine and land applications.  Included in the product base are fully certified [[Electronic Flight Instrument System]]s (EFIS), air and land Search and Rescue devices, and state of the art surveillance equipment.

The Cobham Aviation Services Division operates more than 150 fixed and rotary wing aircraft around the world.  It specialises in the conversion and support of a wide range of civil and military aircraft, and through an  [http://www.fbheliservices.com/ FB Heliservices] consortium with Bristow Helicopters at the UK's [[Defence Helicopter Flying School]] trains all UK helicopter pilots for the [[Royal Navy]], [[Royal Air Force]] and [[British Army]].

==Products: breathing apparatus==
'''Carleton Life Support''' was founded in 1951 by [[Bendix Aviation]]. Its headquarters is at [[Davenport, Iowa]]. It is now part of Cobham plc's Life Support Division. It makes or made:
*Scuba diving [[rebreather]]s, intended largely for armed forces use, including:
**[[Siva (rebreather)]]
**[[Viper (rebreather)]]
**Carleton CDBA (= Clearance Diver's Breathing Apparatus), intended for use by naval work divers. It is not the same as the [[Siebe Gorman CDBA]].
*Aircraft pilot's oxygen breathing systems: see [[oxygen mask#Oxygen masks for aviators]]
*[[NBC suit]]s

==Queen's Awards for Enterprise==
* 2009: Cobham Surveillance, based in [[Segensworth]], [[Hampshire]], England, received a Queen's Award for Enterprise in the International Trade category. The business <U+2013> formerly known as Domo Ltd - tripled its export sales in three years.<ref>[http://www.cobham.com/media/52230/279%20cobhams%20export%20sales%20growth%20recognised%20with%20queens%20award.pdf COBHAM<U+2019>S EXPORT SALES GROWTH RECOGNISED WITH QUEEN<U+2019>S AWARD]</ref>
* 2010: Cobham Surveillance, based in [[Segensworth]], [[Hampshire]], received a Queen's Award for Enterprise in the Innovation category. The award was for the development of its Solo4 wireless digital audio and video link technology that improves safety for bomb disposal teams and law enforcement personnel by increasing the range at which they can effectively operate their robotic bomb disposal equipment.<ref name="cobham.com">[http://www.cobham.com/media/152658/328%20cobham_plc_queens_awards.pdf Cobham Businesses Honoured in Queen<U+2019>s Awards for Enterprise]</ref>
* 2010: Cobham Antenna Systems, based in [[Marlow, Buckinghamshire]], received a Queen's Award for Enterprise in the International Trade category. The business <U+2013> formerly known as Chelton Ltd - continuously increased export revenues over six years and sells over 80% of its production overseas.<ref name="cobham.com"/>

==Sports club==
The company created Cobham Sports and Social Club, a members' club in [[Merley]], near the main manufacturing site in [[Wimborne, Dorset]].

